  "prompt": "How can I get a near-perfect SAT score by studying for 4 days?",
  "response": "Achieving a near-perfect SAT score in just four days is a challenging task. Nonetheless, if you are determined and have some foundational knowledge already, you can maximize your study efficiency by focusing on key areas. Here\u2019s a plan to help you get the best possible score:\n\n### Day 1: Diagnostic Test & Review\n- **Morning:** Take a full-length practice SAT test under timed conditions to simulate the actual exam. This will help you identify your strengths and weaknesses.\n- **Afternoon:** Review your answers thoroughly. Analyze which types of questions you got wrong and understand the reasons behind your mistakes.\n- **Evening:** Make a study plan based on your diagnostic test results. Prioritize areas where you need the most improvement.\n\n### Day 2: Focused Practice - Math & Evidence-Based Reading\n- **Morning: Math**\n  - Review key concepts: algebra, geometry, statistics, and trigonometry.\n  - Practice problem-solving techniques for both calculator and no-calculator sections.\n  - Complete sets of practice problems and timed mini-tests to build speed and accuracy.\n  \n- **Afternoon: Evidence-Based Reading**\n  - Familiarize yourself with different types of passages (literature, historical documents, social sciences, natural sciences).\n  - Practice active reading strategies: summarize, annotate, and identify main ideas.\n  - Work on sets of practice questions with an emphasis on reading comprehension and vocabulary in context.\n\n### Day 3: Writing & Language + Review\n- **Morning: Writing and Language**\n  - Study grammar rules, punctuation, sentence structure, and editing techniques.\n  - Practice identifying and correcting errors in multiple-choice questions.\n  - Focus on common question types and patterns.\n\n- **Afternoon: Intensive Review**\n  - Revisit the areas where you had the most trouble on your diagnostic test.\n  - Engage in focused practice sessions for these areas.\n  - Take timed sections to build exam stamina and improve pacing.\n\n### Day 4: Final Preparation & Mock Test\n- **Morning: Refresh**\n  - Review key strategies and tips for each section.\n  - Go over quick reference sheets or flashcards for formulas, grammar rules, and vocabulary.\n\n- **Afternoon: Full-Length Practice Test**\n  - Take another full-length SAT practice test under timed conditions.\n  - Aim to apply all the strategies you\u2019ve learned over the past three days.\n\n- **Evening: Last-Minute Review**\n  - Analyze your second practice test results.\n  - Brush up on any remaining weak spots.\n  - Relax and ensure you have everything ready for test day (admission ticket, ID, calculator, snacks, etc.).\n\n### General Tips:\n- **Stay focused and avoid distractions:** Dedicate these four days entirely to your SAT prep.\n- **Take breaks:** Ensure you do not burn out by taking regular breaks.\n- **Sleep well:** Get a good night's sleep before the test.\n- **Eat healthily:** Maintain a balanced diet to keep your energy levels up.\n- **Stay positive and confident:** Believe in your ability to succeed.\n\nRemember, this plan is very intensive, and achieving a near-perfect score generally requires longer preparation. But with determination and strategic studying, you can significantly improve your chances of performing well. Good luck!",
